{Even when Black hadn't play ...e5-e4, the move ...f7-f5 overextends Black's
centre. If given the necessary time, Black will play ...Ngf6, ...c7-c6, ...Kc7,
followed by ...e5-e4 and ...Ne5. The f5-pawn, however, gives White dynamic
possibilities.} 1. Bh3 $1 g6 2. g4 $1 {This is the point. As often happens in
this pawn structure, The lack of development does not allow Black to keep his
centre intact. After} e4 3. Nd4 {[%cal Gb1c3,Ge1c1] White's initiative is very
dangerous. Additionally, he can further increase the pressure by means of Nc3
followed by 0-0-0.} *

