{We have a typical position for the setup with c4-d3-e4. Despite weakening the
d4-square, White managed to establish a strong knight in the centre. In the
future, he will consider expanding on the queenside by means of Rb1 followed
by b2-b4, a2-a4 and b4-b5. For the moment, the g2-bishop is temporarily
restricted. In many cases, however, when Black plays ...f7-f5, White can
activate the bishop by means of exf5. It is important to know, that Black
cannot easily get rid of the d5-knight. For example, after} 1... Nxd5 $6 {
White has a thematic reaction -} 2. cxd5 Ne7 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {[%csl Rc7]
[%cal Gc1e3,Ga1c1,Gd1c2,Gc1c7] We have reached a dream position in this
variation. White is better due to his space advantage and the backward c7-pawn.
A natural way to proceed would be Be3 followed by Rc1 and Qc2.} *

