{Whenever Black is ready to play ...f5-f4, White should take on f5. In this
way he also opens the g2-bishop and gets access to the important e4-square.
The diagram position is a typical example. A possible follow-up would be} 1.
exf5 Nxf5 2. b4 Ncd4 3. Nxd4 Nxd4 4. Be3 {[%cal Ge3d4,Gf1e1,Gd1h5,Gd5e7,Gg2e4]
White can already consider taking the d4-knight followed by Re1, thus
occupying the open e-file. Later on, many ideas would be possible. For example
Ne7+ or Qh5 followed by Be4. Of course, White can combine all these threats.}
c6 5. Nc3 {[%cal Gb4b5] After provoking ...c7-c6, White can speed up his
queenside play by means of b4-b5. It is not clear how Black can create
counterplay in this position.} *

