{It is very important to understand that by playing Be3 White prepares d3-d4,
obtaining a favourable pawn structure. Black has two ways to stop the central
advance - ...Nd4 or ...f7-f5. If he makes a waiting move instead, White should
opt for d3-d4. On the diagram, we see a typical position. Black has just
played ...Rae8. Very often this move introduces a slow plan which is based on
driving the d5-knight away. This could be done by means of ...Nc8 followed by .
..Nd8 and ...c7-c6. White, however, should immediately strike with} 1. d4 $1 {
[%cal Ge7c8,Gc6d8,Gc7c6] when after} exd4 2. Nxd4 Nxd4 3. Bxd4 {We reach
another typical position with a tremendous space advantage. White is now
planning to exchange the dark-squared bishops and put his queen in the centre.
After taking control of the centre, he can expand on both wings. If Black
takes the d5-knight, White should take with the c-pawn. Afterwards, the
pressure on the c-file will be very strong.} *

