{Very often Black tries to prepare the advance f5-f4 by doubling his rooks
along the f-file. In such a case, White should react as quickly as possible.
He should either take on f5 and answer gxf5 with f2-f4 or strike on the
queenside. In the concrete position, Black has already played a7-a6 which
speeds up White's queenside play. Therefore, White should go for} 1. b5 $1 {
[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1c7] when the game might continue} axb5 2. cxb5 Bxd5 3. exd5
Na5 4. a4 {White's advantage is undeniable, since the Na5 is poor, and the
c7-pawn is very weak.} *

