{As we have already seen, in this line it is very important to know how to
change the pawn structure in the centre. So far, we have taken a look at two
possible scenarios: 1) opt for d3-d4 when the black pawn is on f7 2)
neutralize Black's attack by means of exf5 followed by f2-f4 Sometimes, it is
possible to play d3-d4 after exchanging on f5. This idea is very effective
when it is preceded by exchanges of minor pieces. Let's take a look at the
position on the diagram. By taking into account the abovementioned
considerations, White shall opt for the following sequence:} 1. Nxf6+ Bxf6 2.
Bxf6 Rxf6 3. exf5 Nxf5 4. O-O c6 5. d4 $1 {forcing a favourable structure for
White. Black will have a weak pawn in the centre and vulnerable king.} *

