{When Black takes on f5 with the bishop, White should proceed with his
queenside play. It turns out that Black cannot easily neutralize the pressure
on the long diagonal. On the diagram, we have a typical example. White should
play} 1. b4 Rae8 2. b5 Nd8 {[%cal Gf5h3,Gh3g2,Gd8e6] It seems that Black is
doing OK. He is planning to follow with ...Ne6 and ...c7-c6 after exchanging
the light-squared bishops via h3. White, however, has a powerful thematic
reaction -} 3. Bxd8 $1 {Eliminating the defender of the b7-square. The idea
can be seen after} Rxd8 4. Ne3 Bh3 5. Bxb7 $1 Bxf1 6. Rxf1 {In this structure,
our light-squared bishop is often more important than a rook. White has more
than enough compensation for the exchange. Besides being a pawn up he
dominates the light squares and has good prospects on the queenside. At the
same time, there are no open files for Black's rooks. Additionally, Black does
not have attacking chances on the kingside.} *

