[EventDate "2019.??.??"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 g6 {A flexible move. Black opts for a fianchetto while the
development of his other minor pieces is delayed for a while.} 3. d4 {
Undoubtedly the most energetic way of handling the position.} exd4 (3... d6 {
is a common alternative that was tried a few times by former world champion
Anatoly Karpov.} 4. dxe5 ({Instead,} 4. Nc3 Nd7 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. Nf3 Ngf6 {
might lead to a well-known line of the KID with g3.}) 4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {
In general, this pawn structure isn't bad for Black at all, but he faces some
concrete problems, mainly because his Kd8 is somewhat unsafe.} 6. Nc3 c6 {
Covering d5 is the best Black can do.} (6... Be6 {runs into} 7. Bh3 $1 $146 ({
Instead, the timid} 7. Bg2 c6 8. Nf3 f6 {led to an equal endgame in Lobron,E -
Karpov,A Walldorf 1997}) 7... Bxc4 ({After} 7... Bxh3 8. Nxh3 f6 9. f4 Nd7 10.
O-O $14 {White's lead in development starts to tell.}) 8. b3 Ba6 ({Equally bad
is} 8... Be6 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Ne4 Nd7 11. Nf3 {, with a powerful initiative.
For instance,} Bd6 12. Nxd6 cxd6 13. Ba3 Ke7 14. Rd1 Nc5 15. Nxe5 $16 {White
regains the pawn and retains all his merits.}) 9. f4 Nc6 {The queens are off
the board, but Black's king is still in big danger.} 10. Bb2 $36) 7. f4 $1 {
White has to hurry to exploit Black's lack of development.} Nd7 ({The
following game illustrates Black's development issues well:} 7... Be6 8. Nf3
Bxc4 $2 {This over-optimistic decision was immediately punished.} ({Better was
} 8... exf4 9. Bxf4 Nd7 10. O-O-O Ke8 11. e4 Ngf6 12. e5 Nh5 13. Be3 Bg7 14.
Be2 $36 {, though even then White has a dangerous initiative.}) 9. Bh3 $1 f5
10. b3 Bb4 11. Bb2 Bd5 12. e4 fxe4 13. O-O-O {Black was crushed in a nice
style in Seirawan, Y - Karpov, A Haninge 1990.}) 8. Nf3 f6 9. Bh3 exf4 10. Bxf4
{Black got under strong pressure in Campiz Jimenez, L - Modesto, R Caguas 2006.
}) (3... Bg7 4. dxe5 Nc6 ({For some reason, the majority of games saw} 4...
Bxe5 {, but this is a clear concession. Indeed, after} 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. Bg2 Ne7 7.
Nc3 d6 8. O-O Nbc6 9. Bf4 O-O 10. Qd2 {White's superiority was obvious in
Voiska, M - Herljevic, R Sibenik 2010}) 5. Nf3 ({Instad, the greedy} 5. f4 $6
d6 6. exd6 cxd6 7. Nc3 Nf6 {offers Black excellent play for the pawn.}) 5...
Nxe5 6. Nxe5 Bxe5 7. Bg2 d6 8. O-O Ne7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Bg5 {The most
challenging way of development.} c6 ({Even worse is} 10... Bg7 11. Qd2 f6 12.
Bh6 $16 {Shinkevich, V - Novikov,S St Petersburg 2006}) 11. Qd3 f6 12. Bd2 $14
{Black suffered from a poor pawn structure and a somewhat awkward placement of
his minor pieces in Akshayraj,K - Volkov,S Rethymno 2012.}) 4. Qxd4 Nf6 ({
Hardly better is} 4... Qf6 5. Qe3+ Qe6 ({After} 5... Ne7 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nd5 {
The pin starts to be very annoying. For instance,} Qd6 8. Bg2 c6 9. c5 $1 Qe5
10. Qxe5 Bxe5 11. Nf3 {Black had big issues with the development of his
queenside pieces. Bevan, P - Guy, D Swansea 2014}) 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Bh3 Qxe3 8.
Bxe3 Nc6 {This position occurred in Kortschnoj, V - Karpov, A Roquebrune 1992.
The natural improvement over White's play was} 9. Nf3 Bg7 10. Rc1 d6 11. Bg2
Be6 12. b3 $14 {White's chances are preferable due to his space advantage.}) 5.
Nc3 Nc6 (5... Bg7 6. Qe3+ Qe7 7. Qxe7+ Kxe7 8. Bg5 c6 {was seen in Navara,D -
Short,N Caleta 2013 Now my new natural idea is} 9. e4 $5 $146 h6 ({Inferior is
} 9... d6 $6 10. c5 h6 11. cxd6+ Kxd6 12. O-O-O+ Ke7 13. Be3 $16) 10. Bf4 d6
11. O-O-O Rd8 12. h3 $14 {Black doesn't have compensation for the weak d6-pawn
and the lack of space.}) 6. Qe3+ {This interrupts Black's natural development.}
Qe7 ({Dubious is} 6... Be7 $6 7. Nd5 Nxd5 8. cxd5 Nb8 9. d6 $1 cxd6 10. Nh3 O-O
{This was Larsen, B-Gheorghiu, F Monte Carlo 1968. Now the simple} 11. Nf4 $146
Nc6 12. Bg2 b6 13. Nd5 $16 {would have put Black in a difficult position with
weak d-pawns and a vulnerable king.}) ({Even worse is} 6... Ne7 $2 7. Qe5 Bg7
8. Nd5 Nfxd5 9. Qxg7 Rg8 10. Qd4 Nb4 11. Qd2 c5 12. Bg2 {Black was
strategically lost in Sorokin,M - Llanos,G Villa Martelli 1997}) 7. Bg2 Bg7 ({
After} 7... Nb4 8. Qd2 Bg7 9. Nh3 O-O 10. Nf4 $14 {The Nb4 is doing nothing.})
8. Nf3 (8. Nb5 $5 {Also seems rather promising.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O d6 10. Qxe7
Nxe7 11. Bf4 Be6 12. b3 {Black had no compensation for his structural
drawbacks in Ivanchuk, V - Majdan, J Warsaw 2009.} *

