{Another aggressive try for Black. We need to react the same way as in the
previous chapter.} 3. d4 $1 {The same strategy. White is trying to open the
position and to prove that 2...f5 is a weakening move. Black has four
different options here.} exd4 {is well met by} (3... e4 {This move makes a lot
of sense. Black is trying to close the position and now the move 2...f5 makes
a lot of sense. The drawback of this move is that White's knight is still on
g1 and now White can use the well-known scheme: Nc3-Nh3-Bg2-f3. White's
position looks very easy to handle and it seems that 3. ..e4 is not solving
Black's problems.}) (3... Bb4+ {This is a well-known idea in many "Dutch"
setups. Black is developing the bishop to an active square before playing
d7-d6.} 4. Bd2 $1 {The right way to react is to exchange the bishops.} Bxd2+ 5.
Qxd2 d6 {with the pawn on f5 the idea of 6.dxe5 dxe5 7.Qxd8 is even stronger
because the pawn on e5 is quite weak. Check the theoretical chapter and
Typical Position 2 for more details.} 6. dxe5 {with the pawn on f5 the idea of
6.dxe5 dxe5 7.Qxd8 is even stronger because the pawn on e5 is quite weak.
Check the theoretical chapter and Typical Position 2 for more details.}) (3...
d6 {This structure is already discussed. White is trying to find an
appropriate moment to take on e5 and to seize the initiative. Check Typical
Position 2 and the theoretical chapter for many interesting details.}) 4. Nf3
$1 {White is aiming for quick development and is not in a hurry to win the
pawn back.} (4. Qxd4 $5 {For those of you who don't want to sacrifice a pawn,
I can recommend this move. White is still slightly better in this structure.})
4... Bb4+ (4... c5 5. e3 $1 dxe3 6. Bxe3 $16 {The extra pawn can't compensate
all those weak squares in Black's camp.}) 5. Nbd2 Nf6 (5... c5 $5 {This is the
most challenging. White's plan now is to finish the development, put the
knight on b3 and open the position with e2-e3.}) 6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O {Then White
is taking the pawn back after Nb3 and it becomes obvious that Black's pawn
will be much better placed on f7.} *

