1. c4 e5 2. g3 f5 {This move usually demonstrates Black's aggressive ambitions,
but the lack of development makes it rather risky.} 3. d4 {As usual, the early
aggressive measures are well met by a break in the centre.} d6 (3... exd4 {
This is the major choice of top players. At the same time, the ensuing pawn
structure clearly favors White.} 4. Nf3 (4. Qxd4 $5 {is another decent option,
but I like the thematic pawn sacrifice.}) 4... Bb4+ ({In case of} 4... Nf6 5.
Nxd4 d5 6. Bg2 c5 7. Nc2 d4 8. O-O Nc6 9. e3 $16 {the vulnerability of the
d4-pawn prevents Black from completing development. Van den Brande, W -
Geboers, J Brasschaat 2011.}) ({The materialistic approach -} 4... c5 5. e3
dxe3 6. Bxe3 Nf6 7. Nc3 Be7 8. Bg2 d6 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 Nc6 11. Qc2 Kh8 12.
Rad1 {left Black in an awful situation, when his pawn structure is poor and
all the pieces are very passive. Carl, M - Silva Filho, A email 2011}) 5. Nbd2
Nf6 6. Bg2 Nc6 (6... c5 7. O-O O-O 8. Nb3 d6 {was seen in a couple of games.
Now my new natural idea is} 9. a3 $146 Ba5 10. Nxa5 Qxa5 11. e3 dxe3 12. Bxe3
Qa6 13. Re1 $16 {Black struggles to complete his development and connect the
rooks, while his king and the d6-pawn are very weak.}) 7. O-O Bc5 8. Nb3 d6 9.
Nfxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 O-O 11. b3 Qe7 12. Bb2 c6 13. e3 {White's structural
advantage was undeniable in Hechl, G - Bontems, C email 2015.}) (3... e4 {
This is the most consistent choice, which was made by world champion Magnus
Carlsen.} 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Nh3 {I like this flexible way of development.} ({
Possible is also} 5. Bg2 $5 c6 6. d5 Bb4 7. Bd2 Na6 8. Nh3 O-O 9. O-O cxd5 10.
Nxd5 Nxd5 11. cxd5 Bxd2 12. Qxd2 $14 {Svidler,P - Carlsen,M Astana 2012}) 5...
c6 {Black is focused on building up a strong pawn centre.} (5... Bb4 {Quite a
committal move.} 6. Bd2 {That's the point! The threat of 7.Nxe4 practically
forced Black to give up his bishop.} Bxc3 7. Bxc3 O-O 8. d5 d6 9. Nf4 $16 {
Black's position was cramped, while the Bc3 was very strong. Markowski, T -
Heberla, B Warsaw 2004}) ({Another way of development,} 5... Nc6 {, reduces
Black's control of the e4-pawn, so after} 6. Bg2 Bb4 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 O-O 9.
f3 $14 {White had strong pressure on it in Belkhodja, S - Prie, E France 1992})
6. f3 $1 {This standard break comes in time.} Bb4 ({After} 6... d5 7. cxd5 cxd5
8. Bg5 Bb4 9. Nf4 $16 {Black was very close to a collapse in Miles, A -
Vegetti, E Mendrisio 1989.}) 7. Qb3 c5 ({Hardly much better is} 7... Bxc3+ 8.
bxc3 d6 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O $36 {Black will not manage to hold his pawn centre
for too long, so White's bishops are going to be very powerful.}) 8. Be3 Qa5 9.
O-O-O {Black faced serious problems with development in Miles, A - Gavrikov, V
Moscow 1990.}) (3... Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 d6 (5... exd4 6. Qxd4 Qf6 7. Nf3
Nc6 8. Qd2 Nge7 9. Bg2 O-O 10. Nc3 $16 {Ksieski,Z - Poetsch,K Bayern 2015}) 6.
dxe5 dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Nf3 Nd7 {took place in Thomas,T - Marthinsen, A
email 2017 In my opinion, White can make use of his lead in development by} (
8... e4 9. Nd4 Nf6 10. Nc3 c6 {was seen in Markowski, T - Gulko, B Polanica
Zdroj 1996.} 11. O-O-O $146 {Now most energetic was} Ke7 (11... Kc7 $2 12. Bh3
g6 13. Ndb5+ cxb5 14. Nxb5+ Kb6 15. Rd6+ $18) 12. f3 Na6 13. Bg2 exf3 14. exf3
$36 {Black's king feels very unsafe in the centre.}) ({In case of} 8... Nc6 9.
Nc3 Nf6 10. O-O-O+ Bd7 11. Bh3 e4 {White might extend his initiative with} 12.
Ng5 $1 Ke7 13. Rxd7+ $1 Kxd7 14. Bxf5+ Ke7 15. Ngxe4 $16 {It would be hard to
prevent White from advancing the passers in the long run.}) 9. Bh3 $1 $146 g6 (
9... Nh6 10. Nc3 c6 11. e4 $14) 10. g4 $1 e4 11. Nd4 {, and Black has concrete
problems to solve. Play might continue:} Ne5 12. gxf5 Nxc4 13. fxg6 hxg6 14.
Ne6+ Bxe6 15. Bxe6 Nd6 16. Bxg8 Rxg8 17. Nc3 {The complications end in an
unpleasant endgame in which Black has a few weak pawns.}) 4. Nc3 Be7 ({In case
of} 4... Nf6 {White can benefit from liquidating into an endgame:} 5. dxe5 dxe5
6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Nf3 {, and now there is no good way of covering the e5-pawn:}
Bd6 (7... e4 {Thompson, I - Mah, K England 1997} 8. Nd4 $146 c5 9. Nb3 Nc6 ({
Equally bad is} 9... Be6 10. Bg5 Nbd7 11. O-O-O Ke8 12. f3 $16) 10. Bg5 Ke8 11.
f3 exf3 12. exf3 Kf7 13. O-O-O Be6 14. Nd5 $16) (7... Nc6 8. Bg5 Be7 9. O-O-O+
Ke8 10. Nd5 $16) 8. c5 Bxc5 9. Nxe5 Ke7 10. Bg2 c6 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Nd3 Bd6 {
After natural play from both sides this position was reached in Andreasson, I
- Renman, N Sweden 1996 Now I prefer} 13. b4 $1 a6 (13... Ne5 14. b5 Bd7 15.
Rb1 $36 {is very annoying, too.}) 14. Be3 Ne5 15. Nc5 {White's positional
advantage is undeniable - Black fails to develop his queenside pieces.}) (4...
e4 {was tried on the highest level, but it seems premature. White should
immediately challenge the centre:} 5. f3 $1 Nf6 6. Bg2 exf3 7. Nxf3 {White has
a big development advantage, and that should tell in all cases:} g6 ({The
passive} 7... Be7 {cannot be recommended either:} 8. O-O O-O 9. d5 Na6 10. Nd4
Ng4 11. e4 fxe4 12. Nxe4 Rxf1+ 13. Qxf1 {Black is doomed to passive defence in
a position in which he lacks space. Pfalz, J - Fric, P email 2007.}) 8. O-O Bg7
9. Bg5 O-O 10. e4 $16 {Foisor, C - Muzychuk, A Chalkida 2009}) 5. Bh3 $1 {
A decent way to pose Black concrete problems - the lack of development makes
it difficult to safely cover the f5-pawn in this position.} Na6 {The main
drawback of this awkward move is that the knight neglects the centre.} ({After
} 5... exd4 6. Qxd4 Nf6 7. Bg2 Nc6 8. Qd2 Ne5 9. b3 c6 10. Bb2 {White had a
clear structural superiority in Ranaldi, L - Pavlovic,M Stockholm 2019}) (5...
e4 6. f3 Nf6 {, as in Allicock,R - Lund, S New York 2019 should be challenged
with} ({Bad is} 6... exf3 $6 7. Nxf3 Nf6 8. Nh4 g6 9. Bh6 $16) 7. fxe4 $146
Nxe4 8. Nxe4 fxe4 9. Qc2 O-O 10. Qxe4 Nc6 11. Bxc8 Rxc8 12. Nf3 $14 {Black
struggles to claim adequate compensation for the pawn.}) ({The most
illustrative line starts with} 5... Nf6 6. Nf3 e4 7. Nh4 g6 8. Bh6 {, and now
Black's king is stuck in the centre. Play might continue:} Kf7 9. O-O Ng8 {
This position appeared in Ronat, O - Fister, B email 2011. Now my natural
improvement over White's play is} 10. Bc1 $1 $146 Bxh4 11. gxh4 Qxh4 12. Bg2
Nf6 13. f3 exf3 14. Rxf3 $36 {The vulnerability of Black's king and the
powerful bishop pair offer White a dangerous initiative.}) 6. dxe5 dxe5 7.
Qxd8+ Bxd8 8. Nf3 $1 {The vulnerability of the e5-pawn prevents Black from
developing his pieces again.} e4 ({Hardly better is} 8... Nb4 9. O-O Nc2 10.
Rb1 e4 11. Nh4 Bxh4 12. gxh4 Be6 13. b3 $36) 9. Nd4 Ne7 ({After} 9... g6 10. f3
exf3 11. exf3 Nf6 12. Be3 Kf7 13. O-O-O Re8 14. Rhe1 $14 {White's forces are
much better mobilized.}) 10. b3 {Black's setup looked quite cramped in Storme,
I - Kadric, D Lisbon 2019.} *

