{[%evp 0,11,16,-18,-23,-46,21,-50,7,14,20,0,6,-9]} 1. c4 e5 2. g3 h5 $5 {
Alpha Zero style. This move is patronized by such players as Morozevich and
Rapport. White tried almost all sensible moves here, but I think the best is}
3. Nf3 $1 Nc6 (3... h4 4. Nxh4 Rxh4 5. gxh4 $16 {Is just winning for White}) (
3... e4 4. Nh4 $1 {The point of White's idea. The knight is very well placed
on h4. It stops h5-h4 and can go to f5. In the meantime, the pawn on e4 is
quite weak.} Be7 5. Nf5 {followed by 6.Nxe7 with an advantage. The position
remains full of tactical nuances, so I suggest you to study very carefully
theoretical chapter 3.}) 4. Nc3 {White is trying to prove that the inclusion
of h7-h5 is just a waste of time. When White stops the idea of h5-h4, then he
should just play like in the other setups depending on the Black's scheme.} Bc5
(4... d6 {is well met by} 5. d4 $1) 5. Bg2 d6 6. e3 {We saw this position
without h7-h5 in the first database. It is obvious that d2-d4 is coming and
Black's can't make use of h7-h5} *

