1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 (3. Nc3 $5 {works quite well against 3...f5, but
here 3...Nf6 followed by Bb4 is the problem and the line which I wanted to
avoid.}) 3... f5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. e3 {this is my recommendation. I like that
White is quite flexible here - White can develop calmly after d2-d3 or just
try to open the centre after d2-d4 in some lines. The "g1" knight is always
well placed on "e2" in those setups.} g6 {Is a popular scheme of development.
White can't play the d3-e4 anymore (at least not without losing a tempo).} (
5... d5 $5 {the most ambitious reply} 6. cxd5 Nb4 7. d3 Nbxd5 8. Nxd5 Nxd5 9.
Nf3 {Critical position for this variation. I think White is better here. The
the structure is quite flexible and White can choose from b2-b4, d3-d4 or
e3-e4 breaks depend on Black's response. The -d3 pawn could be vulnerable in
some cases, but we can say the same about the pawn on -e5.}) (5... Bb4 {
this move doesn't work very well here. White can continue 6.Nge2 avoiding
doubling his pawns on the c-file and it is not so clear what the bishop is
doing on "b4"}) (5... d6 {is too modest and should be meet by 6.Nge2 followed
by d2-d4}) (5... Nb4 $6 {looks too artificial for me.} 6. d3 c6 {this is the
point of Black's previous move} 7. a3 Na6 8. Nf3 $14) 6. d4 d6 7. Nge2 Bg7 8.
b3 {The idea here is that White wants to delay castling by playing moves like
Bb2, Qd2, etc... The point is that if Black closes the centre with e5-e4 then
White has strong idea h2-h4 followed by Nf4 and sometimes h4-h5. In these
positions, the rook on h1 is perfectly placed.} *

