1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nc6 (2... Nf6 3. Bg2 Nc6) 3. Bg2 f5 {This is the only
independent conitnuation.} ({Both} 3... g6) ({and} 3... Nf6 4. Nf3 {leads to
the lines that are covered in other Chapters.}) 4. Nc3 Nf6 (4... g6 5. d3 Bg7
6. e4 d6 7. Nge2 {is another transposition.}) (4... Bb4 {doesn't make sense
now because of} 5. Nd5 Bc5 6. e3) 5. e3 {I like this flexible way of
development.} ({Instead,} 5. d3 Bb4 6. Bd2 O-O 7. Nf3 d6 8. O-O a5 9. a3 Bc5 {
might lead to a long strategical struggle, when Black's counter-attacking
abilities on the k-side shouldn't be underestimated.}) 5... d5 {Among Black's
possibilities, this is the most ambitious try.} ({Another standard setup is
connected with finachetto} 5... g6 6. d4 d6 7. Nge2 Bg7 8. b3 $1 {It turns out,
that White can favorably delay castling.} O-O 9. Bb2 e4 {Black can hardly do
without this advance for too long.} (9... Qe8 10. Qd2 e4 ({Hardly better is} 
10... Bd7 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. cxd5 Ne7 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Rc1 $14) 11. Nf4 Bd7 12.
Ncd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Rc8 {was seen in the game Petersons,A-Polugaevsky,L Vilnius
1960 Now White should have played} 14. h4 $1 $146 Ne7 15. Nf4 Qf7 16. Bf1 h6
17. Be2 {, followed by 0-0-0. Black's king is under permanent pressure, while
most of his pieces are very passive.}) ({I also checked} 9... Bd7 10. Qd2 e4
11. Nf4 Rb8 {Black's idea is to initiate some play on the q-side with a7-a6
and b7-b5, but this is too slow.} 12. h4 a6 13. Bf1 Ne7 14. Be2 b5 15. d5 $36)
10. h4 $1 {An important move, that secures the f4-spot for the knight.} Be6 ({
Ineffective is} 10... Nb4 11. Nf4 Nh5 12. Nce2 $16 {Zurek,M - Langner,L
Czechia 1999}) 11. Nf4 Bf7 12. Bf1 $1 {The Bg2 has made its job, so White is
relocating it in order to advance his k-side pawns.} Re8 13. Be2 Nb8 {This
move demonstrates, that Black lacks any constructive counter-attacking ideas.}
14. g4 $1 fxg4 15. Bxg4 $36 {White had a strong initiative in Watson,R -
Barata,A email 2017}) (5... Bb4 {I was surprised to discover, that this move
was tried by many strong GM's, including Caruana, Sasikiran and others. In my
opinion, the Bb4 is definitely misplaced.} 6. Nge2 (6. Nd5 $5 {is another
promising idea.}) 6... O-O 7. O-O d6 (7... Bxc3 {this move was made by Fabiano,
but giving up the dakr-squared bishop seems a clear concession} 8. Nxc3 d6 9.
d4 e4 ({The attempt to maintain the tension with} 9... Qe8 {is well met by} 10.
Nd5 $1 Qf7 11. b3 e4 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. f3 $16 {Broom,M - Rosen,D Birmingham
2001}) 10. f3 exf3 11. Qxf3 Bd7 12. b3 Rb8 13. Bb2 Qe8 14. Rae1 $16 {White had
both the space advantage and pair of bishops in Granda Zuniga,J - Caruana,F
Tromsoe 2014}) 8. Nd5 Nxd5 (8... e4 9. d4 exd3 10. Qxd3 Bc5 11. b3 $16 {
Vaulin,A - Polgar,S Kecskemet 1992}) 9. cxd5 Ne7 10. d4 $1 {This standard
advance makes the placement of Bb4 even more awkward.} Ba5 ({After} 10... e4
11. Qa4 $1 c5 (11... Nxd5 $2 12. a3 $18) 12. a3 Ba5 13. dxc5 dxc5 14. b4 cxb4
15. axb4 Bc7 16. Rd1 $16 {the strong d5-passer makes White's superiority
undenieble.}) 11. b4 $1 {This resourse makes it possible to complete the
development very quickly.} Bb6 (11... Bxb4 $2 12. Qa4 $18) 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. a4
a6 14. Qb3 Kh8 15. Bb2 $16 {Black suffered the lack of harmony and weak Pe5 in
Markowski,T - Brustkern,J Dresden 2006}) (5... Nb4 {Too artificial is} 6. d3 c6
7. a3 Na6 {This was Sokolov,I - L'Ami,E Amstelveen 2016 Now my new natural
idea is} 8. Nf3 $146 d6 9. O-O Be7 10. b4 O-O 11. b5 $36 {White has the upper
hand.}) (5... d6 6. Nge2 Be7 (6... g6 {transposes to 5...g6.}) 7. O-O O-O 8. d4
Qe8 9. Nd5 Bd8 ({After} 9... Nxd5 10. cxd5 Nd8 11. Bd2 $14 {the pressure on
the Pc7 is gonna be annoying.}) 10. Nec3 e4 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 {was seen in
Vachier Lagrave,M - Savina,A Drancy 2016 Now I mostly like the energetic} 12.
Nd5 $146 Bd8 13. f3 exf3 14. Qxf3 {Black is doomed to passive defence.}) 6.
cxd5 Nb4 {The vulnerablity of d3-spot allows Black to regain the pawn.} 7. d3
Nbxd5 8. Nxd5 Nxd5 9. Nf3 Bd6 ({In case of} 9... Bb4+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2
Qd6 12. O-O O-O {White can exploit the weakness of Pe5 with} 13. e4 $1 Ne7 (
13... Nf6 14. Qc3 Re8 15. Ng5 $16 {Kokarev,D - Diu,V Vladivostok 2012}) 14. d4
fxe4 15. Nxe5 $16 {Kramnik,V - Bartel,M Dortmund 2012}) 10. O-O Nf6 {The most
common retreat. Black is intending to castle, so he moves his knight away from
a2-g8 diagonal.} ({Even worse is} 10... Nb6 11. e4 $1 O-O 12. exf5 Bxf5 ({After
} 12... Qf6 13. Ng5 Bxf5 14. Bxb7 Rad8 15. Bg2 {White was just a pawn up in
Flores,D - Bachmann,A Villa Martelli 2010}) 13. d4 e4 14. Ng5 $16) (10... O-O {
was played in 2 games, and now my new natural idea is} 11. Qb3 $146 Be6 12. Nd4
exd4 13. Bxd5 Bf7 14. Qxb7 $16 {Black has no compensation.}) 11. b4 $5 {
I like this way of extending on the q-side.} Qe7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. b5 Kh8 14. a4
{The pressure along diagonal a1-h8 offers White a stable advantage. Ginsburg,M
- Ibragimov,I Las Vegas 2005} *

