{This is the starting tabya of Chapter 5. We discuss similar setups in the
first database. Now the main difference is that Black's knight is still on g8
which provides Black with some different options: White's main idea is to play
Nge2 followed by d2-d4. We should do this against almost any move as 5... Bf5,
5...Nge7, 5...Nf6. The main problem is the semi-waiting move 5...a6} 5... a6 {
You can wonder why this move is so dangerous and is the main line. The main
reason is that against the setup with 6.Nge2, Black wants to play h5!} 6. Nf3
$1 {[%emt 0:00:01] White's idea is very simple. He wants to push d4 and to
answer exd4 with exd4 followed by 0-0 and d4-d5. Black sometimes tries to
fight for the d4 square by playing Bg4 but then after h3 Black is forced to
give up the bishop pair. Probably the best for Black is to play 6...Nf6 7.0-0
8.0-0 which transposes to the first database.} (6. Nge2 $5 Ba7 (6... h5 $5) 7.
O-O h5 $1 {Black starts an active play on the kingside. This position is the
main reason why Black chooses this move order. The objective analysis and the
statistics show that White should try another scheme on move 6.}) 6... Ba7 7.
d4 exd4 8. exd4 $1 {White has full control of the centre, the bishop on a7 is
out of play and the idea d4-d5 is sometimes quite unpleasant for Black. An
important nuance is that after:} Bg4 9. Be3 {Black can't put more pressure on
d4 and 10. h3 is coming.} *

