11. Nc3 c6 12. dxc6 Nxc6 13. Qb3 $14 {White was better due to his strong
unopposed Bg2 in Chernin, A - Anand, V Paris 1995.}) 7. d4 Ba7 8. O-O O-O ({
The aggressive} 8... h5 {is well met by} 9. b4 $1 h4 10. b5 axb5 11. cxb5 Ne7
12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Qxd8+ Kxd8 14. Rd1+ Ke8 15. a4 {The endgame was difficult
for Black in Bex, L - Terryn, E Blankenberge 2014.}) 9. h3 Re8 10. b3 exd4 11.
exd4 Bf5 12. Be3 Ne4 {This position took place in the correspondence game
Mcmahon, F - White, R email 2018 Now the simple} 13. Rc1 $146 Nxc3 14. Nxc3 Qd7
15. Kh2 {would have put Black in a passive position with a serious lack of
space.}) (5... Bf5 6. a3 a5 {This preventive move weakens b5.} ({Nobody tried} 
6... Bd3 {, but this move looks challenging} 7. b4 Bb6 8. Qb3 Nf6 9. Bb2 O-O
10. Na4 e4 11. Ne2 $14 {In this original position White's bishops are very
powerful.}) ({After} 6... Nf6 7. b4 Bb6 8. d3 Qd7 9. h3 O-O 10. Nge2 Rfe8 11.
Bb2 $14 {White had the more harmonious setup in Tembo, E - Garach, N Durban
2017}) ({Another natural option to consider is} 6... a6 7. Nge2 Nf6 8. d3 Qd7
9. h3 h5 10. b4 Ba7 11. Bb2 O-O {Natural play by both sides led to this
position in Schunk, T - Jandke, M Loeberitz 2017. At this point White could
have benefited from delaying castling by} 12. g4 $1 $146 hxg4 13. hxg4 Nxg4 (
13... Bxg4 14. Kd2 $1 Ne7 15. Qg1 $36) 14. Ng3 Be6 15. Nce4 f6 16. Bf3 Ne7 17.
Rh4 $36 {Black's king feels very unsafe.}) 7. d3 Nf6 (7... Nge7 8. Nge2 Qd7 9.
h3 O-O 10. b3 Bb6 11. Bb2 Bg6 12. Qd2 $14 {Collas, S - Leconte, M
Saint-Quentin 2015}) 8. Nge2 O-O 9. h3 h6 10. g4 {A somewhat committal move,
but White gains some space for his minor pieces.} Bd7 ({I've also examined} 
10... Bh7 $146 11. Ng3 Rb8 12. O-O Ne7 13. d4 Bb6 14. f4 $14 {Black is too
passive.}) 11. Ng3 Rb8 {This was Damljanovic, B - Zhigalko, S Rijeka 2010.
Black covered the b7-pawn, so his knight can be relocated to g6 or even h4.
Here I suggest the new and natural continuation:} ({After} 11... Nh7 12. h4 $1
Ne7 13. g5 f5 14. d4 Ba7 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. gxh6 gxh6 17. Bxb7 Rb8 18. Bf3 {
Black doesn't have enough play for the pawn.}) 12. O-O Ne7 13. d4 Ba7 (13...
exd4 14. exd4 Bb6 15. b4 c6 16. d5 cxd5 17. g5 $1 hxg5 18. Bxg5 $36 {White's
pieces are much more active, so Black is under big pressure.}) 14. dxe5 dxe5
15. b4 Ng6 16. Nce4 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 $14 {The poor Ba7 makes Black's position
rather unpleasant.}) (5... Nge7 6. Nge2 a6 {The most flexible. Black secures
the retreat of his bishop in advance.} (6... Bf5 7. d4 Bb6 8. a3 Qd7 {, as in
Sameh, A-Yasser, A Alexandria 2010 should be naturally met by} 9. b4 a6 10. d5
Nd8 11. h4 $1 {A multi-purpose move which prevents Black from exchanging
bishops and also vacates h3 for White's bishop.} h6 12. e4 Bh7 13. f4 $36 {
Black's pieces desperately lack space.}) ({The prophylactic} 6... Bb6 7. d4
exd4 {, as in Pyrich,G - Veen,H England 1999 , is well met by} 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9.
exd4 O-O 10. O-O {, and now} Nf5 {runs into} 11. Nd5 $1 Re8 (11... Bxd4 $2 12.
g4 $18) 12. Nxb6 axb6 13. b3 $14 {The bishop pair offers White long-lasting
pressure.}) (6... O-O 7. O-O a6 8. b3 Ba7 ({Ineffective is} 8... Bg4 9. h3 Bh5
10. g4 Bg6 11. d4 Ba7 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Ba3 Qe8 14. Nd5 $16 {Dunsbach, R -
Poetsch, G Schoeneck 2017}) 9. d4 {is also a transposition.} (9. Bb2 $5 Bf5 10.
d4 exd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. exd4 Rb8 13. Qd2 {might also suffice for an edge.})
9... exd4 ({The more ambitious} 9... f5 {is traditionally met by} 10. dxe5 $1
dxe5 11. Ba3 Re8 12. Qc2 Be6 13. Rad1 {Black suffered from a lack of harmony
in Bonoldi, F - Szopa, J email 2014.}) 10. Nxd4 $1 {This precise move allows
White to cover the d4-pawn and keep the opponent's dark-squared bishop locked.}
({Instead,} 10. exd4 Nf5 11. d5 Ne5 {looks acceptable for Black.}) 10... Nxd4
11. exd4 {transposes to 6...0-0.} Nf5 ({The immediate} 11... Rb8 {doesn't
really change the character of play:} 12. Re1 Re8 13. Bb2 Bf5 14. Ne2 Ng6 15.
Qd2 b5 16. cxb5 axb5 {This was Talpak, T - Dosi, A email 2017. Now White
should have played} 17. d5 $1 Qd7 18. Bd4 Bxd4 19. Nxd4 $14) 12. Ne2 Rb8 13.
Bb2 Re8 14. Qd2 h6 15. Rac1 Bd7 16. Rfe1 c6 17. Nf4 $14 {White had a big space
advantage for free in Gustafsson, J - Schlosser, P Emmendingen 2017.}) 7. O-O
Ba7 8. d4 h5 {Only this aggressive continuation has an independent value.} (
8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. exd4 O-O 11. b3 {transposes to 6...0-0.}) (8... O-O
9. b3 {is also a transposition.}) 9. b4 $1 {This energetic move makes it
possible for White to exploit the drawbacks of the early h7-h5} ({Instead,} 9.
d5 Nb8 10. h3 f5 {closes the position in Black's favor.}) 9... h4 (9... exd4
$146 10. exd4 Nxb4 {This is the only way to justify the early exchange on d4.}
({Ineffective is} 10... h4 11. b5 axb5 12. cxb5 Na5 13. Re1 c6 14. Nf4 $14 {
Black doesn't have time to make any threats on the kingside.}) 11. d5 $1 {
A strong move that yields White tempi to develop his initiative.} a5 12. Bb2
Nf5 ({The consistent} 12... h4 {runs into} 13. Nb5 $1 Nf5 14. Nxa7 Rxa7 15. Re1
O-O 16. a3 Na6 17. g4 Nh6 18. Qd4 $18) 13. Re1 O-O 14. Nf4 h4 15. Ne4 $36 {
The vulnerability of his king and the poor coordination between his pieces
make Black's position very difficult.}) 10. b5 axb5 (10... hxg3 11. bxc6 gxf2+
12. Rxf2 Nxc6 13. Nd5 $16 {doesn't offer Black adequate compensation for the
piece.}) ({Hardly better is} 10... Na5 {Bender, D - Caldara, S Cortina
d'Ampezzo 2013} 11. dxe5 hxg3 12. hxg3 Nxc4 13. bxa6 $16) 11. cxb5 Na5 12. dxe5
hxg3 13. hxg3 dxe5 {We have been following the game Tsoi, D - Yakubboev, N
Konya 2018. In my opinion, had White played} 14. Qa4 $1 $146 Bb6 15. Rd1 Bd7
16. Ba3 c6 17. Rab1 {, it would have been very hard for Black to withstand the
attack.}) 6. Nf3 {In my opinion, this way of development is the most promising.
} (6. Nge2 {is by far the most common, but after} Ba7 7. O-O h5 $5 {Black can
quickly develop some play on the kingside. The Ne2 is located somewhat
passively.}) 6... Ba7 ({The most ambitious} 6... f5 {was never seen in
practice. Most probably, White should play} 7. d4 Bb4 8. dxe5 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3
dxe5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. e4 Nf6 12. O-O $1 Nxe4 13. Ng5 {The bishop pair and
the lead in development provide White with more than sufficient compensation
for the pawn.}) (6... Nf6 7. O-O O-O {is covered with 2...Nf6 & 3...Bc5.}) ({
Pinning the Nf3 doesn't help Black to stop d3-d4:} 6... Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 8. O-O
Ba7 {This was Zwardon, V - Fedorchuk, S Katowice 2017} 9. d4 exd4 10. exd4 Nxd4
11. g4 Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 Bg6 13. Qxb7 $18) 7. d4 {As usual, when the dark-squared
bishop is located on the a7-g1 diagonal, the d3-d4 break is even more
effective!} exd4 8. exd4 Bg4 9. Be3 Nge7 ({The other way of development is
problematic, too:} 9... Nf6 10. h3 Bh5 11. g4 Bg6 12. d5 Bxe3 $2 ({The lesser
evil was} 12... Ne7 13. Bxa7 Rxa7 14. Nd4 {, but even then White is dominating
over the board.}) 13. dxc6 $18 {Black was already lost in Gomez Jurado, L -
Vicient Calvo, R Barcelona 2015}) 10. h3 Bxf3 (10... Bh5 $2 11. g4 Bg6 12. d5
Bxe3 13. dxc6 {leads to material losses.}) 11. Bxf3 Nf5 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. Qd3
Qd7 14. g4 Nxe3 15. fxe3 O-O 16. O-O-O {Black's position is rather unpleasant
in view of the poor Ba7 and the weak doubled c-pawns. Fridman, D - Kobo, O
Minsk 2017} *

