{This position is a very important part of our repertoire.} 4. Nf3 $1 {The
concept here is similar as in the previous chapters. White wants to play d2-d4
as soon as possible and avoids all those Bb4 lines. Black has a wide choice of
systems, but most of them just transpose to the other chapters of the database.
The only move which has an independent value is 4...g6} (4. Nc3 {Is the main
move, but then after} Bb4 {we reach a "Reversed Rossolimo" and we need to
study tons of theory. According to the current theory, Black has decent
chances here.}) 4... g6 (4... Bc5 {transposes to the lines with 3...Bc5}) (4...
d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 {[%emt 0:00:01] Transposes to "Reversed Dragon" which we
checked in Part}) 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. O-O Re8 {Black makes
all useful moves and creates the positional threat 9...Nxd4 10.Qxd4 Ne4. This
is the critical position of the line. The best setup for White is Nc2, Qd2, b3,
Bb2, Ne3, Rd1} (8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4 d6 {Is not that challenging and it is
analyzed in the theoretical chapter.}) 9. Nc2 $1 {Typical idea in similar
structures. White has a space advantage and tries to keep more pieces on the
board.} d6 10. Qd2 $1 {another important move. Strange looking move, but it
makes a lot of sense. White defends the knight on c3 before playing b2-b3.
After an immediate 10.b3, Black can continue 10...Bf5 followed by 11...Ne4.
Black has a lot of options in this position and you can check all of them in
the theoretical section. Black doesn't have any dynamic options and White can
enjoy his space advantage after b2-b3, Bb2, Ne3, etc...} *

