1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. Nf3 {This move perfectly fits into our
repertoire and also limits Black's possibilities.} ({Instead,} 4. Nc3 Bb4 {
might lead to a Rossolimo with an extra tempo for White. I am not sure that
this is enough for an advantage.}) 4... g6 {only this seems to have an
independent value.} (4... Bc5 5. O-O d6 6. Nc3 O-O (6... a6 7. e3 Ba7 8. d4 {
hardly has any independent value, since} Bg4 $6 9. h3 exd4 10. exd4 Bxf3 11.
Bxf3 {is just bad for Black.}) 7. e3 {This theoretical position is covered
with 3...Bc5.}) (4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 {is another transposition.}) 5. d4 {
As often, this advance allows White to force a favourable pawn structure.} exd4
({After} 5... e4 $6 6. Ng5 d5 7. O-O $16 {Black's pawn centre will be
destroyed.}) 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. O-O Re8 {The strongest. Since Black
cannot yet move his d-pawn and develop the bishop, he makes a useful move and
invites White to show his cards.} ({After} 8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4 d6 10. Qh4 Ng4 11.
Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Bg5 f6 13. Bf4 Ne5 14. Nd5 c6 15. Ne7+ Kf7 16. Nxc8 Raxc8 17. b3
$14 {White had both the better pawn structure and the bishop pair in
Ovchinnikov, A - Savitskiy, S Moscow 2009}) 9. Nc2 {This concept is typical
for such a pawn structure: White has a space advantage, so he should avoid
unnecessary simplifications. The knight is heading towards d5.} ({In case of} 
9. Nxc6 dxc6 $1 10. Qb3 Qe7 11. Bf4 Ng4 $1 {Black's active piece play fully
compensates for the doubled pawns. So, W - Artemiev, V Bucharest 2019}) 9... d6
10. Qd2 $1 {A decent prophylactic move that makes it possible for White to
comfortably develop his queenside pieces.} ({Somewhat premature seems} 10. b3
Bf5 11. Bb2 Ne4 $1 12. Bxe4 Bxe4 13. Ne3 Nd4 14. Nxe4 Rxe4 15. Qd3 Qe8 16. Rad1
c6 {Chances were mutual in Gelfand, B - Bacrot, E Albert 2002.}) 10... a5 ({
Too provocative is} 10... Bf5 11. Ne3 Ne4 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. f3 {, and the Be4
is in danger.} Bf5 14. Nxf5 gxf5 {This was Dubov, D - Artemiev, V Moscow 2018.
Here I prefer the natural} 15. Rb1 $5 $146 Bd4+ 16. Kh1 Be3 17. Qd3 Bxc1 18.
Rbxc1 Qf6 19. e3 $14 {Black doesn't have adequate compensation for his
structural drawbacks.}) ({The following plan also doesn't seem to solve
Black's problems:} 10... Be6 11. b3 Qc8 12. Bb2 Bh3 13. f3 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 $14)
11. b3 Nb4 12. Ne3 $1 $146 {As was mentioned before, White should try to avoid
exchanges. In this particular case, the Nb4 is misplaced} ({The only preceding
game saw} 12. Bb2 Nxc2 13. Qxc2 Bf5 14. Qc1 c6 {Black was close to equality in
Matlakov, M - Artemiev, V St Petersburg 2018}) 12... Ng4 {Eventually Black
provokes White to swap the knights, but now his king is getting somewhat
exposed.} 13. Nxg4 Bxg4 14. Bb2 ({But not} 14. Bxb7 $6 Rb8 15. Bg2 Qf6 16. Bb2
Rxe2 $1 17. Nxe2 Qxb2 {, and Black is fine.}) 14... c6 15. h3 Be6 16. Ne4 $36 {
The vulnerability of the Kg8 starts to tell.} *

