{This is the starting position of Chapter 7. The idea of 3...h6 is to wait for
Nc3 and then to develop the bishop on b4.} 4. Nf3 $5 {I manage to find an
interesting alternative to the main line.} e4 {the most principle reply.} (4...
Nc6 $5 5. O-O {and White is ready to open the position. The move h6 is just
waste of time.}) 5. Nd4 Nc6 6. Nc2 {This move can look strange, but is quite
typical for "English Opening". White is delaying the development, but this is
compensated by the weakness of e4. The position resembles 2...c6 lines which
were discussed in database 1. White's plan is to castle and to open the centre
with d2-d3 or d2-d4.} (6. Nxc6 $6 dxc6 {Is very good for Black. The bishop on
c8 can come to play and Black can put some pressure on the semi-open d-file.
It is hard for White to keep the balance here.}) 6... d5 {is the most
energetic reply.} 7. cxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qe6 {This is the Critical position. I
found almost unexplored resources for White here.} 9. d4 $1 (9. O-O $6 Bd6 $1 {
and Black is in time to finish the development}) 9... exd3 10. Qxd3 Bd6 11. Nb5
$1 {White exchanges the bishop and can enjoy a long-term advantage due to his
bishop pair.} *

