1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 h6 {This somewhat ''mysterious'' move was tried by
many top players, including Carlsen, Anand , Adams and more. The main idea is
to wait until White develops his queen's knight, and then after Bf8-b4 Black
might consider the typical e5-e4 advance, since g5 has been taken from the
knight. At the same time, in case White deviates from moving his knight, h7-h6
might turn out to be a loss of tempo.} 4. Nf3 {I find this move challenging,
even though 4.Nc3 and 4.a3 are much more common.} e4 ({After} 4... Nc6 5. O-O {
The waste of tempo for h7-h6 starts to tell. For instance,} e4 ({Hardly better
is} 5... Bc5 6. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 7. d4 $16) ({The modest} 5... d6 {isn't an
attractive option either:} 6. Nc3 Be7 7. d4 O-O 8. h3 Bf5 9. d5 Nb8 10. Nh4 Bh7
11. e4 Nbd7 12. Be3 {Black's position was too cramped in Zimmermann, R - Braun,
G Germany 2017.}) 6. Ne1 Bc5 7. Nc3 Qe7 {Karlsson,M - Bjornsson,S Reykjavik
2013} 8. e3 O-O 9. d3 exd3 10. Nxd3 Bb6 11. Nf4 $16) 5. Nd4 {The current
position is sort of a reversed Alapin with a lot of pressure on e4.} Nc6 ({
The other natural continuation is} 5... d5 6. d3 $1 {White starts to attack
the opponent's pawn centre.} ({Instead,} 6. cxd5 Qxd5 {leads to an interesting
position that is very similar to the 3...c6 line. The only difference is that .
..h7-h6 was played instead of ...c7-c6, and I am not sure this is in White's
favour .}) 6... exd3 (6... dxc4 7. dxe4) 7. cxd5 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 Nxd5 9. Qxd3 O-O
10. O-O Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bc5 {Gelfand, B - Inarkiev, E Magas 2016} 12. Bf4 $146 c6
13. Rfd1 Re8 14. Nb3 $14) 6. Nc2 d5 ({Bad is} 6... Ne5 $2 7. b3 d5 8. cxd5 Bf5
9. Ne3 Bg6 10. Bb2 $16 {Carlstedt,J - Hillarp Persson,T Helsingor 2012}) ({
Another move that cannot be recommended is} 6... Bc5 $6 7. Nc3 Qe7 8. O-O O-O {
, as in Saulin, D - Glek, I Moscow 2014. Now White could have exploited the
artificial location of Black's pieces by} 9. Ne3 $1 $146 Bxe3 10. fxe3 d6 11.
b3 $16) 7. cxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qe6 ({The other retreat} 8... Qe5 {Zwardon, V -
Stocek, J Czech Republic 2016 can be traditionally met by} 9. d4 $146 exd3 10.
Qxd3 Bf5 ({After} 10... Bc5 11. Be3 O-O 12. Bxc5 Qxc5 13. Qb5 $14 {The
''Catalan'' pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal is rather annoying.}) 11. e4 Rd8
12. Qe2 Bg4 13. f3 Be6 14. Bf4 $14 {White should be able to make use of his
pawn majority on the kingside.}) 9. d4 {By making this move, White
demonstrates the awkward location of the Qe6.} ({Less promising is} 9. O-O Bd6
10. d3 exd3 11. exd3 O-O 12. d4 Qg4 13. Nb5 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Bg4 $11 {Mamedyarov,
S - Inarkiev, E Izmir 2016}) 9... exd3 10. Qxd3 Bd6 ({The more aggressive} 
10... Ne5 {doesn't offer Black much because of} 11. Qd1 Bc5 12. O-O O-O {
This was Melkumyan, H - Stocek, J Batumi 2018. Now White should have exchanged
the strong Bc5:} 13. Be3 $146 Bxe3 14. Nxe3 c6 15. Qd4 $14 {White's pieces are
far more active.}) 11. Nb5 {Liquidating the strong Bd6 is an undisputable
achievement for White.} O-O 12. Nxd6 Rd8 13. Bf4 Nh5 {This is aimed at
avoiding an isolated d-pawn.} 14. Be3 Rxd6 {This position occurred in Hammer,J
- Vallejo Pons,F Moscow 2017. In my opinion, White could have liquidated into
a slightly better endgame with} 15. Qe4 $5 $146 Qxe4 16. Bxe4 Nf6 17. Bg2 Bf5 (
17... Be6 18. Bc5 Bd5 19. e4 Re6 20. f3 $14) 18. Rc1 Be4 (18... Nd5 19. Bc5 Rd7
20. O-O $14) 19. f3 Bd5 20. a3 Re8 21. Kf2 Bb3 22. Rhe1 $14 {The activity of
Black's pieces is neutralized, whereas White's bishops will be very strong in
the long run.} *

