[FEN "r1bqk2r/ppp1npbp/2np2p1/4p3/2P1P3/2NP2P1/PP3PBP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 7"]
[PlyCount "7"]

{The most popular, but slightly passive move. Black is not blocking the f-pawn
(as in 6...Nf6 lines) and wants to finish the development and only then to
play f7-f5. The best idea for White is to finish the development with
Nge2-0-0-Be3 and then to put his knight on d5 followed by an expansion on the
queenside. Black's main plan is connected with f7-f5, but then White can take
on f5 in an appropriate moment and open his g2-bishop} 7. Nge2 O-O (7... Nd4 $6
8. Nxd4 $1 exd4 9. Ne2 {White has an advantage here due to his better pawn
structure. The plan is simple - White wants to expand on the queenside. If
Black defends the pawn on d4 with c7-c5 then White transfer the knight to d5
via f4.}) 8. O-O Be6 (8... f5 {This move is usually met by Nd5 and then it is
hard for Black to start an active play on the kingside. The thematic f5-f4 is
not possible and the h6-g5 plan is well met by exf5!}) 9. Nd5 Qd7 10. Be3 {
The most flexible continuation. White is developing his pieces and is delaying
the decision on which side to start an active play. Some possible plans are: 1.
b2-b4 with or without Qd2 2.d3-d4 3. If Black plays 10...Nd4, then 11. Bxd4!
exd4 12.Ndf4!.} *

