1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. e4 Nge7 {Quite a flexible
way of development, when the f7-pawn remains unlocked. On the other hand, in
comparison to 6...f5, Black's setup is less active and his attacking chances
on the kingside are limited.} (6... Be6 {Black can try to play Be6 and Qd7
before developing the knight.} 7. Nge2 Qd7 8. Nd5 Nce7 (8... Nd8 9. d4 c6 10.
Ne3 exd4 11. Nxd4 Bh3 12. Ndf5 Bxf5 13. exf5 $16 {White is clearly better and
went to win a nice game in 1-0 (26) Grischuk, A (2771)-Svidler,P (2722) Moscow
2010}) 9. d4 $1 c6 10. Ne3 Bh3 (10... exd4 11. Nxd4 Bh3 12. Ndf5 Bxf5 13. exf5
$16 {1-0 (47) Maletin,P (2575)-Pasiev,R (2313) Samara 2011}) 11. O-O Bxg2 12.
Kxg2 exd4 13. Nxd4 $14 {Black doesn't have any compensation for the weak pawn
on d6 1-0 (48) Kasparov,G (2800)-Short,N (2635) Linares 1990}) 7. Nge2 O-O (
7... a6 {was tried a few times by the Azeri GM Rauf Mamedov, but it looks like
a loss of time since the confrontation will take place on the opposite side of
the board.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Nd5 h6 (9... Nxd5 10. cxd5 Ne7 11. d4 exd4 12. Nxd4
c5 13. dxc6 Nxc6 {This was Soffer,R - Movsziszian,K Hersonissos 2017. Now the
natural} 14. Be3 $146 Bd7 15. Qd2 {would have left Black without compensation
for his inferior pawn structure.}) 10. Be3 f5 11. Rc1 g5 {Rice,C - Morris, N
Crawley 2016} 12. f4 $1 $16) ({Deviating from castling with} 7... Be6 {makes
little sense:} 8. Nd5 h6 9. Be3 Nd4 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Bd2 c6 12. Nf4 {White
was clearly better in Grischuk, A - Andriasian, Z Dubai 2014.}) (7... Nd4 {
doesn't look like an attractive option either:} 8. Nxd4 exd4 9. Ne2 {This pawn
structure seems very comfortable for White since Black lacks a clear plan. For
instance,} c5 (9... O-O {is well met by} 10. b4 $1 c5 11. Rb1 b6 12. O-O Bb7
13. g4 {White was firmly in control on both sides of the board in Hassel, D -
Boik, A Edmonton 2004.}) 10. O-O O-O {is covered below.} 11. Bd2 Nc6 ({In case
of} 11... Rb8 12. a4 a5 {Foster, J - Jeffries, M Birmingham 2006} 13. Nf4 $146
Qc7 14. h4 $14 {White takes the upper hand on the kingside.}) 12. Nf4 Rb8 13.
a4 Ne5 14. b4 {Starostits, I - Stojanovski, D Bled 2002}) 8. O-O Be6 (8... f5 {
is traditionally met by} 9. Nd5 h6 (9... Nxd5 10. cxd5 {is covered in the
chapter with 6....f5.}) 10. Rb1 {, with the usual expansion on the queenside.}
g5 ({Equally good is} 10... a5 11. a3 ({The flexible} 11. Be3 $5 Kh7 12. Qd2
Be6 {This position occured in Zenzera, A - Morozov, E Kostroma 2012. Now my
new natural idea is} 13. b3 $5 $146 Qd7 14. f4 $14 {White has the more
harmonious setup.}) 11... g5 (11... fxe4 {The change of pawn structure} 12.
dxe4 {doesn't seem to solve all Black's problems. For instance,} Nd4 13. Nxd4
exd4 {Van Leent,D - Le Duigou,J email 2014} 14. Nf4 a4 15. Bd2 Bd7 16. h4 {
The pawn majority offers White excellent prospects on the kingside.}) 12. exf5
Nxf5 13. b4 axb4) 11. exf5 Nxf5 ({I've also examined} 11... Bxf5 12. b4 a6 13.
a4 Qd7 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 15. b5 $14 {White's initiative on the queenside speaks
for itself.}) 12. b4 Ncd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Be3 c6 15. Nc3 Bf5 {We have been
following the correspondence game Ramik, J - Keskowski, T ICCF email 2012,
where a draw was agreed. In my opinion, had White played} 16. Ne4 Qd7 17. Bxd4
exd4 18. b5 {Black would have been doomed to a passive defence in an
unpleasant position.}) (8... Nd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Ne2 c6 {By making this move,
Black shows that he is aware of the possibility of opening files on the
queenside.} ({The prophylactic} 10... a5 $5 {should be considered seriously.}
11. b3 {This prevents Black from expanding with a5-a4 and vacating b2 for the
bishop.} Bd7 {This position was tested in a few correspondence games. At this
point I offer a fresh strategic idea:} 12. a4 $5 {This move looks like a
positional concession, but it heavily limits Black's counter-attacking
abilities, while the weakness of b4 is hard to exploit.} Nc6 13. Qd2 Nb4 (13...
f5 14. Bb2 Qe7 15. Rae1 $14 {The d4-pawn is very weak.}) 14. Ba3 c5 15. Bxb4
axb4 16. Rae1 $14 {White is better.}) (10... c5 {is covered below.}) 11. b4 a5
12. b5 {It is in White's interest to open the c-file since this will isolate
the d4-pawn.} cxb5 13. cxb5 d5 {This position took place in the classical game
Portisch, L-Smyslov, V Monte Carlo 1968. A clear improvement over White's play
is} 14. Nf4 $1 $146 dxe4 15. Bxe4 Ra7 16. Re1 b6 17. Bf3 $16 {White is
dominating the board.}) 9. Nd5 {The Nd5 is very stable, which is the main
merit of White's setup.} Qd7 (9... f5 10. Be3 Qd7 {is just a transposition.})
10. Be3 (10. Bg5 $5 f6 11. Be3 f5 {might lead to the same.}) 10... f5 {The
most logical and ambitious continuation. might lead to the same. is just a
transposition.} ({Too artificial seems} 10... Rac8 {, with the idea to swap
the light-squared bishops. White ignores that by playing} 11. Qd2 Bh3 12. b4
Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Nxd5 14. cxd5 Ne7 15. Rac1 c6 (15... f5 16. f3 c6 17. dxc6 bxc6
18. a3 $14) 16. dxc6 Nxc6 17. b5 Ne7 18. Qb4 {Black got under strong
positional pressure in Brueckner, T - Vogel, R Germany 1988.}) ({In case of} 
10... Nd4 {it makes sense to give up the dark-squared bishop.} 11. Bxd4 $5 exd4
12. Ndf4 c6 13. Nxe6 Qxe6 14. b4 $14 {Lizak,S - Morkisz, B Poland 2008}) ({
The waiting} 10... Rae8 {can be well met by} 11. d4 $5 exd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13.
Bxd4 $14 {Black had typical structural issues in Backes, J - Martins, A Nova
Petropolis 2015.}) 11. b4 $5 {I don't see a reason for delaying this standard
advance, but this position is almost unexplored.} (11. Qd2 {is by far most
common, but I don't like the fact that after} Rf7 12. Rac1 Raf8 13. b4 f4 14.
gxf4 Bh3 {Black obtains a definite attacking potential, as was proven in a few
games.}) 11... Rae8 ({The ''greedy''} 11... Bxd5 $2 12. cxd5 Nxb4 {is easily
refuted by} 13. Rb1 c5 14. dxc6 Nbxc6 15. Qb3+ Rf7 16. Qxb7 Qxb7 17. Rxb7 {
Black was lost in Fauber, R-Celorio, E Lone Pine 1974.}) (11... a6 {doesn't
change much:} 12. Rc1 Kh8 ({After} 12... Rf7 13. b5 $1 axb5 14. cxb5 Bxd5 15.
exd5 Na5 16. a4 {White's advantage is undeniable, since the Na5 is poor, and
the c7-pawn is very weak.}) 13. Qd2 Rf7 {We have been following the game
Lombardy, W-Malich, B Leningrad 1960. Now the most ambitious continuation
would have been} 14. b5 $1 $146 axb5 15. cxb5 Bxd5 16. exd5 Na7 17. a4 Nac8 18.
a5 $16 {Black's position is very cramped.}) ({The attempt to take over the
initiative with} 11... f4 $146 12. gxf4 Bh3 {runs into} 13. Rc1 $1 {, and
Black has nothing better than liquidating into a bad endgame:} Nxd5 14. cxd5
Qg4 15. Ng3 exf4 16. dxc6 bxc6 17. Qxg4 Bxg4 18. Bd2 fxg3 19. hxg3 $16 {
The weak c-pawns make Black's position very difficult.}) 12. b5 Nd8 13. a4 Nc8
14. exf5 Bxf5 (14... gxf5 15. f4 c6 16. Ndc3 Bf7 17. Rb1 {White's chances are
preferable due to his space advantage and superior piece coordination.}) 15.
Nec3 c6 16. Nb4 Bh3 17. Bxh3 Qxh3 18. Ne4 {White was clearly better in Mueller,
H - Breite, W email 2012.} *

