1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. e4 f5 7. Nge2 Nf6 {The
most natural way of development.} ({The original} 7... Nh6 $5 {should be
seriously considered since it was employed by many strong players such as
Svidler, Short and others. By placing the knight on f7, Black avoids the nasty
pin along the h4-d8 diagonal.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Nd5 Nf7 {The Nf7 is placed rather
harmoniously. At some point, Black might consider ...Nc6-d4!?, hoping to
extend the diagonal of the Bg7 and gain the e5-square for his other knight.} ({
Hardly better is} 9... g5 10. exf5 Bxf5 {This position occurred in Smejkal,J -
Dautov, R Germany 1991. Now my new natural idea is} 11. Rb1 $146 a5 12. a3 Kh8
13. b4 axb4 14. axb4 Nd4 15. Ne3 $14 {The pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal
causes Black definite problems.}) ({Or} 9... Be6 10. Rb1 Qd7 11. b4 Nd8 12. b5
Kh8 13. a4 {Black suffered from lack of space in Fierro Baquero, M - Dzagnidze,
N Doha 2011.}) 10. exf5 {A well-timed exchange.} ({Less precise is} 10. Be3 $6
Nd4 $1 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Bd2 c6 {Black has excellent play.}) 10... Bxf5 {
Natural play from both sides led to this position in Salzmann, S - Orban, C
email 2012 In my opinion, White shouldn't deviate from the most consistent} 11.
b4 $5 $146 Qd7 12. b5 Ncd8 ({After} 12... Nd4 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Nb4 Rab8 15. f4
$14 {Black's minor pieces lack good squares.}) 13. Rb1 c6 14. Ndc3 Bh3 ({
The attempt to develop some activity on the kingside by} 14... Ne6 15. Be3 Nd4
{fails to} 16. Ne4 $1 Bg4 17. f3 Bf5 18. Nxd4 exd4 19. Bd2 Ne5 20. Qb3 $14 {
Black ends up in a passive position with no real counterplay.}) 15. Qa4 Bxg2
16. Kxg2 Ne6 17. Ne4 {White has the more active position. Play might continue:}
d5 18. bxc6 {This leads to favourable simplifications.} Qxc6 19. Qxc6 bxc6 20.
cxd5 cxd5 21. N4c3 Rfd8 22. Ba3 {White has a slight but long-lasting
positional advantage.}) 8. Nd5 (8. O-O {is by far the most popular, but White
can benefit from the early occupation of the d5-square.}) 8... O-O (8... Nxd5
9. cxd5 Ne7 10. O-O O-O 11. Be3 {This position can also arise after 6...Nge7,
in case Black decides to capture on d5. The pressure along the c-file will
sooner or later force Black to play ...c7-c6.} c6 ({The delay of c7-c6 hardly
solves the problems:} 11... Bd7 12. Rc1 c6 13. dxc6 Bxc6 14. Qb3+ Kh8 15. Bg5
$14) ({Bad is} 11... f4 $2 12. gxf4 exf4 13. Nxf4 Bxb2 14. Rb1 Bg7 15. d4 {
Black was strategically lost in Donchenko, A - Galliamova, A Riga 2019.}) 12.
dxc6 bxc6 13. Rc1 Be6 ({The careless} 13... a5 $6 14. Bg5 $1 Bf6 15. Bxf6 Rxf6
16. d4 $16 {led to an extremely dangerous situation, where Black is close to a
collapse. Shyam,S - Savchenko,B Moscow 2012}) 14. b3 Qd7 {This was Senior,L -
Finch,R email 2018. In my opinion, White should have continued} 15. f4 $146 Rf7
16. Qd2 Raf8 17. Kh1 $14 {Black has no compensation for his structural
drawbacks.}) ({In case of} 8... h6 {White can immediately push b2-b4-b5
without wasting time on preparatory moves.} 9. b4 $5 O-O {This position was
tested in a few games. Now I have a new natural idea:} ({Of course not} 9...
Nxd5 10. cxd5 Nxb4 $4 11. Qa4+ $18) 10. exf5 $146 Bxf5 (10... gxf5 {is hardly
an improvement:} 11. b5 Ne7 12. Nxf6+ Rxf6 13. a4 a6 14. Rb1 axb5 15. axb5 Rf7
16. O-O $14 {White's chances are preferable.}) 11. b5 Ne7 12. Nxf6+ Rxf6 13.
O-O ({Possible is also} 13. Bxb7 Bh3 14. Rg1 Rb8 15. Be4 {, and Black doesn't
have sufficient play for the pawn, even though White's king is located in the
centre.}) 13... c6 14. bxc6 bxc6 15. Nc3 $14) ({The following interesting pawn
sacrifice was recently successfully employed on GM level:} 8... f4 $5 9. gxf4
O-O {At this point White should have deviated from his initial paths and play}
10. h4 $1 {, with the idea to open the g-file.} ({Instead, after} 10. O-O Nh5
11. fxe5 dxe5 {Black had excellent compensation for the pawn due to his
control over the dark squares in Nguyen, T - Van Foreest, J Prague 2020.})
10... Bg4 ({The following line illustrates White's intentions well:} 10... Nh5
11. f5 $1 gxf5 12. Bg5 Qd7 13. Qd2 Qf7 14. O-O-O Kh8 15. Bf3 $36 {Black's king
got under strong pressure.}) 11. f3 Be6 12. h5 $1 {This is the most consistent.
} ({After} 12. fxe5 dxe5 13. Bg5 Qd7 {Black still has some compensation for
the pawn.}) 12... Nxh5 13. f5 Bf7 {Black regained the pawn, but his king is
somewhat exposed now.} 14. fxg6 hxg6 15. Bh3 $1 {An important resource. The
bishop joins the attack now.} Qh4+ (15... Nd4 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. Bg4 c6 18. Nf4
$16) 16. Kd2 Nf4 ({After} 16... Qf2 {Black might liquidate into an endgame,
but it hardly helps:} 17. Qf1 Qxf1 18. Rxf1 {White is dominating the board.})
17. Nexf4 exf4 18. Qf1 $1 {White's king will soon be re-located to the
queenside, while Black's king is under a strong attack.}) 9. Bg5 {This is the
point! Now ...h7-h6 is impossible, so Black has to deal with an unpleasant pin
for a while.} Be6 ({Somewhat artificial is} 9... Ne7 10. Nxf6+ ({Less precise
is} 10. Qd2 {, as in Wang, Y - Ivanchuk, V Beijing 2013.} Nexd5 11. cxd5 f4 $1
12. gxf4 h6 {, and Black has a rich counterplay.}) 10... Bxf6 11. Bxf6 Rxf6 {
This position occurred in Matamoros Franco, C - Sasikiran, K Beijing 2008 The
most logical continuation at this moment seems} 12. exf5 $146 Nxf5 13. O-O c6
14. d4 $1 {This advance forces a favourable pawn structure for White.} Qb6 15.
dxe5 dxe5 16. b3 Be6 17. Qe1 Raf8 18. Nc3 $14 {Black doesn't have adequate
compensation for his weak e5-pawn.}) 10. Qd2 Qd7 {Black avoids the pin and
connects his rooks.} 11. O-O Nh5 ({Black might double the rooks along the
f-file, but it hardly offers him any attacking chances. For instance} 11... Rf7
12. b4 fxe4 (12... Raf8 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. b5 Nd8 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bxf6 Rxf6
17. d4 $14) 13. dxe4 Raf8 14. f3 $1 {A decent restricting move that secures e3
for White's bishop.} Ne8 15. Be3 Nd8 16. Qd3 c6 17. Ndc3 $14 {Black was doomed
to passive defence in Geider, F - Sandstroem, L email 2014.}) (11... Rae8 12.
b4 Nh5 {The most ambitious - Black's main hopes are connected with ...f5-f4.} (
{Too passive seems} 12... Nd8 13. exf5 Bxf5 {Hamark,J - Grigorov,G Sweden 2017.
The knight's retreat reduces Black's control of d4, so White should have played
} 14. Nxf6+ $146 Bxf6 15. Bxf6 Rxf6 16. d4 $14 {, taking the upper hand in the
centre.}) 13. b5 Nd8 14. exf5 Bxf5 {This transposes to 11...Nh5.} ({Worth
attention is} 14... gxf5 $5 {, which was never tried in practice yet. White
should play} 15. Bf3 $1 Bf7 16. Bxd8 Qxd8 17. Rab1 {In this complex position
White's chances seem preferable, mostly due to his powerful Bg2. For instance,}
c6 18. bxc6 bxc6 19. Nb4 c5 20. Nd5 Nf6 21. Nxf6+ Qxf6 22. Bc6 Rc8 23. Bg2 $14)
) 12. exf5 Bxf5 {Black prefers to keep the f-file open to double his rooks.} ({
The other recapture,} 12... gxf5 {, runs into} 13. f4 $1 {, and Black's pieces
are sort of stuck on the kingside. Play might continue} Kh8 14. Rae1 Rae8 15.
b4 Nd8 16. Ne3 Nf7 17. Bh4 exf4 18. gxf4 Nh6 19. h3 {White had better
prospects in Serper, G - Sakaev, K Kherson 1991}) 13. b4 Rae8 ({The attempt to
