vacates g1 for the minor pieces.} Kh8 ({I also examined} 12... Be6 13. Nd5 Qd7
14. Rc1 Rae8 15. Qb3 $14) 13. Qd2 Be6 {This position occurred in Gabuzyan, H -
Naroditsky, D Saint Louis 2019. Now White should have covered the c4-pawn with}
14. b3 $1 {, making d3-d4 practically unstoppable.} Qd7 15. d4 exd4 16. Nxd4 {
White's superiority is undeniable.}) 9. h3 Qd7 ({Black's second choice by
statistics is} 9... Nd7 10. f4 $1 {The most energetic response.} ({The most
popular} 10. Be3 {is well met by} Nd4 $1 11. Bxd4 exd4 12. Nb5 c5 $1 13. Nxd6
Qb6 14. Nb5 a6 15. Na3 Qxb2 {led to an unclear position in Schuh, K - Lang, M
Germany 1999.}) 10... f5 ({Possibly safer is} 10... exf4 $5 {, though it
doesn't look like an attractive option either:} 11. Bxf4 Nd4 12. Qd2 Re8 13.
Nxd4 Bxd4+ 14. Kh2 a6 15. Rac1 c5 16. Ne2 Bg7 17. d4 cxd4 18. Nxd4 {Black got
under long-lasting positional pressure in Berlinger, G - Pugh, J email 2013.})
11. exf5 gxf5 {We have been following the game Doeres, H - Hoerr, M Germany
2004. At this moment White should have prepared the important d3-d4 advance by}
(11... Bxf5 $2 12. Bd5+ Kh8 13. g4 $18 {Vandenbussche, T - Barbe, T Worriken
Buetgenbach 2004}) 12. b3 $1 Nf6 13. Be3 Qd7 14. d4 {Black faces serious
structural problems.}) (9... Ne8 {was played in dozens of games. Curiously,
nobody tried the natural} 10. b3 $5 {, with the idea to meet} f5 11. exf5 gxf5
{with} 12. d4 $1 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Ne2 c5 15. Nf4 Bf7 16. Bxb7 Rb8 17. Bd5
$14 {White regained the pawn and obtained an excellent position with control
over the light squares.}) 10. Kh2 Nh5 {The most ambitious choice. Like in the
KID, Black is aiming for a quick ...f7-f5.} ({The less active retreat} 10...
Ne8 {hardly makes much sense. For instance,} 11. Nd5 f5 12. exf5 gxf5 13. Bg5
$5 {, provoking Black to weaken his king.} h6 (13... Kh8 14. Qd2 Nd8 15. f4 c6
16. Ne3 {was much better for White in Grabinsky, V - Stubberud, O Calvi 2005})
14. Bh4 Kh7 15. Qd2 Nd8 16. d4 $16 {The difference in activity of pieces was
obviously in White's favour in Gschwendtner, S - Kratochvil, M Czechia 1996.})
11. g4 {This somewhat provocative move allows White to prevent Black from
pushing f7-f5.} ({Worth attention is also} 11. Rb1 $5 f5 12. exf5 gxf5 13. b4 {
, with decent prospects on the queenside.}) 11... Nf6 (11... Nf4 $6 12. Nxf4
exf4 13. Bxf4 {White is just a pawn up.}) 12. Nd5 Ne8 13. Be3 f5 {Black cannot
activate his pieces without this committing move, but with such a poor Ne8 it
can only backfire.} 14. exf5 gxf5 15. gxf5 Bxf5 16. Ng3 Bg6 17. f4 $36 {
The poor location of the Ne8 starts to tell, so White manages to take the
upper hand on the kingside.} *

