[White "Main Ideas - Chapter 11"]
[Black "Move Orders"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A27"]
[Annotator "GM Michael Roiz"]
[PlyCount "12"]

{[%evp 0,12,43,-8,-8,-79,-49,-43,-2,-7,16,9,9,-48,-14]} 1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nc6 3.
Nc3 {The problem with this move order, however, is that it gives Black an
alternative - 3...Nf6 4.Nf3 Bb4 when we have a well-known theoretical position
which is not a subject of this survey. Therefore, while this is a possible
option, the main suggestion of Roiz is to start with 3.Bg2.} f5 {Black stops
the immediate d2-d4 and wants to continue the development. White's best plan
in this position is to prepare d2-d4.} 4. Nf3 $1 {There are 3 different setups
for Black.} Nf6 (4... d6 5. d4 $1 e4 6. d5 $1 {An important idea. White can
continue 6.Nh4 or 6.Ng5 but the text move is stronger. The main point is that
White wants to play Nd4 next after any other move except 6.. .Ne5} Ne5 7. Nxe5
dxe5 {We reach a very important structure. And I found important improvements
over the current theory which you can check in the theory section. White's
main idea is to play f2-f3 and to exchange the pawn on e4. Afterwards, he can
put pressure on Black's central pawns. The problem is that the immediate 8.f3
can be met by 8...Bc5! and Black has counterplay on the dark squares.} 8. Be3
$1 {This move is my improvement. It contains two ideas. One is to take control
of the diagonal while the another one is to prepare a long castle. White is
playing next f2-f3, Qc2, 0-0-0 with an initiative.} (8. f3 $2 Bc5 $1)) 5. d4 e4
6. Nh4 {You should be already familiar with this idea. White is gaining tempo
by attacking the f5 pawn and wants to relocate the knight to f4 square via g2.
Black needs to choose between two setups. The more active with d7-d5 and
slightly more passive with d7-d6.} d5 {This is the most challenging approach.
Here, before relocating the knight to f4, White needs to play 7.Bg5.} (6... d6
7. Ng2 $1 {White's play is quite simple here. Our plan is Nf4, Bg2, 0-0, b2-b3,
and break the centre with f2-f3!}) (6... g6 {It is possible to delay the
decision where to put the d-pawn for a while. But with the pawn on g6, it
makes sense to include 7.Bg5 before maneuvering the knight to f4.}) *

