1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {The problem with this move order, however, is that
it gives Black an alternative - 3...Nf6 4.Nf3 Bb4 when we have a well-known
theoretical position which is not a subject of this survey. Therefore, while
this is a possible option, the main suggestion is to start with 3.Bg2.} f5 4.
Nf3 {Since the immediate d2-d4 isn't possible (like after 2...f5) White
prefers to develop his knight first in order to make it work in the future.}
Nf6 (4... d6 {can be seen on high level, too. Again White should continue with}
5. d4 e4 {, and now the most energetic is} 6. d5 $1 Ne5 ({Worse is} 6... exf3
7. dxc6 bxc6 8. exf3 Nf6 9. Bg2 Be7 10. f4 Bd7 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 $16 {
Keber,E - Milde,L email 2012}) 7. Nxe5 dxe5 8. Be3 $1 $146 {By covering the
a7-g1 diagonal White makes the f2-f3 break more effective.} ({Less convincing
is} 8. g4 Bc5 9. Qb3 Nf6 10. Qb5+ Nd7 {Aronian,L - Short,N Caleta 2018}) 8...
Nf6 9. f3 Be7 10. Qc2 (10. fxe4 $5 O-O 11. Bg2 f4 12. Bg1 {doesn't offer Black
enough play for the pawn, but I still prefer the text.}) 10... O-O 11. O-O-O
$14 {White's prospects are clearly better due to his space advantage and more
active pieces.}) (4... g6 5. d4 e4 6. Nh4 ({I've also examined} 6. d5 $5 $146
exf3 7. dxc6 dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. exf3 Be6 10. Be3 Nf6 11. O-O-O+ Ke8 12. Na4
{White has a slight advantage due to his more active pieces, but Black might
be able to neutralize it in the long run.}) 6... Bg7 7. e3 Nf6 ({After} 7...
Nge7 8. Ng2 d6 9. Nf4 O-O 10. h4 {White can slowly expand on the queenside,
while Black doesn't have any counterplay.}) 8. Ng2 O-O 9. Nf4 d6 10. h4 {
The French pawn structure favours White since Black's pieces are not ready for
active measures on the kingside. In particular, the Bg7 is ineffective.} Re8
11. a3 a5 12. b3 Ne7 13. Bb2 {White was better in Malinowski, D - Zaleski,L
Warsaw 2019}) 5. d4 e4 ({Clearly worse is} 5... d6 $6 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Qxd8+
Kxd8 8. Bg5 Be6 9. Bh3 {Black got under strong pressure in Van Deursen, P -
Voss, A email 2000.}) 6. Nh4 d5 {This is the most ambitious concept. Black is
trying to build up a strong pawn centre, even though his pieces are not really
supporting it at the moment.} (6... d6 7. Ng2 $1 {By relocating the knight
White gains more control of d5 and makes the standard f2-f3 break more
effective.} Be7 ({Somewhat more active, but also riskier is} 7... g6 8. Bg5 Bg7
({Hardly better is} 8... h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. e3 Qf7 11. Nf4 Bg7 12. Ncd5 O-O {
Dziedzic, A - Pajak,J ICCF email 2015 Now after} 13. h4 Kh7 14. Be2 $36 {
Black will struggle to complete the development of his pieces.}) 9. Nf4 Ne7 ({
The alternative} 9... O-O {doesn't looks attractive either:} 10. h4 Qe8 11. e3
{This feels dangerous, but after} Ng4 $2 12. Nfd5 Qf7 13. Nb5 {Black suffers
from the loss of a pawn in Doyle,H - Melaugh,G Bunratty 2017.}) 10. e3 O-O 11.
h4 h6 {Black forces the exchange of White's powerful bishop, but it seriously
weakens his pawn structure.} 12. Bxf6 Rxf6 13. Be2 Bd7 {This was Schandorff,L
- Wiwe,A Svendborg 2019. Here I prefer the energetic} 14. g4 $1 $146 fxg4 15.
Bxg4 h5 16. Bxd7 Qxd7 17. Qc2 $36 {Black's setup looks quite shaky.}) 8. Nf4
O-O 9. Bg2 Qe8 10. O-O Qf7 ({Equally good is} 10... Bd8 11. f3 exf3 12. exf3
Qf7 13. b3 Ne7 14. Qd3 $14 {Damljanovic,B - Organdziev,O Skopje 2013}) 11. b3
Bd7 12. f3 exf3 13. exf3 {White has the more active position and the knights
are heading towards e6. Negulescu,A - Nicolaide,V Predeal 1988}) (6... g6 7.
Bg5 Bg7 8. e3 O-O 9. Ng2 d6 ({In case of} 9... h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Nf4 Ne7 12.
h4 d6 13. Be2 c6 14. Qb3 Rb8 15. g4 $1 $36 {White takes over the initiative on
the kingside.}) (9... Ne7 10. Nf4 h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. h4 d6 {, as in Galyas,M
- Webb,L Daventry 2020 might be well met by} 13. Ncd5 $1 $146 Nxd5 14. cxd5 Kh7
15. Rc1 Bd7 16. Bc4 $16 {The pressure along the c-file and the vulnerablity of
his king make Black's position difficult.}) 10. Nf4 Ne7 {leads to a position
that is covered with 6...d6.}) 7. Bg5 Bb4 {The most challenging move. By
pinning the Nc3 Black reduces White's control of d5.} ({The modest} 7... Be7 {
runs into} 8. e3 O-O 9. Ng2 dxc4 10. Bxc4+ Kh8 11. Nf4 {White was dominating
the board in Wengholm,A - Rydstrom,T Eskilstuna 2019}) 8. e3 ({Curiously, the
most natural} 8. cxd5 $6 {was only once met by the strong} Nxd5 $1 9. Bxd8 Nxc3
10. Qb3 Nxe2+ 11. Kd1 Nexd4 12. Qe3 Be6 {Black has a powerful attack.
Mchedlishvili, M - Rathnakaran, K Taleigao 2019.}) 8... O-O 9. Ng2 h6 10. Bxf6
Rxf6 11. Nf4 Ne7 {Hillarp Persson, T -Sasikiran,K Stockholm 2018} 12. Qb3 Bxc3+
13. Qxc3 c6 14. h4 Ng6 15. Ng2 Be6 16. c5 $14 *

